         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W. ¶ June 9 /69 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ Since I last wrote two boxes have come from you one (I believe per Somersetshire) some little time since and the other per Wellesley just arrived...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">69.06.09a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">June 9 /69</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Since I last wrote two boxes have come from you one (I believe per Somersetshire) some little time since and the other per Wellesley just arrived</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have finished the <name key="Verbenaceae">Verbenaceae</name> and <name key="Myoporineae">Myoporineae</name> the latter have taken a long time because I had carefully to examine the ovaries — I have now packed up all your specimens and they go in a box they are sending from Kew with some other specimens for you I trust they will reach you safe.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In revising <name key="Verbenaceae">Verbenaceae</name> I have thought the best course is to limit <name key="Chloanthes">Chloanthes</name> to the species with decurrent leaves which have a distinct habit with appreciable characters in the corolla and anthers and to reduce the <name key="Quoya">Quoya</name>s with the non decurrent western <name key="Chloanthes">Chloanthes</name> to <name key="Pityrodia">Pityrodia</name> which has in every respect all the <name key="Quoya">Quoya</name> characters.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There is no doubt you are right in transferring <name key="Sparthothamnus">Sparthothamnus</name> to <name key="Verbenaceae">Verbenaceae</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>M's discussion of <name key="Verbenaceae">Verbenaceae</name> in B68.03.04, pp 151-8, includes the transfer of this species and the proposal to unite <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Teucridium</seg>, p. 153.</p>
               </note> but I cannot agree in uniting Teucridium which has the 4-lobed ovary and 4-lobed fruit separating into dry nuts of <name key="Oxera">Oxera</name> and is in my opinion as distinct from Spartothamnus as any two genera of <name key="Verbenaceae">Verbenaceae</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Myoporineae">Myoporineae</name> must I presume be kept distinct from <name key="Verbenaceae">Verbenaceae</name> as they differ in the aestivation of the corolla as well as in the inferior radicle<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>The following discussion is responding to M's treatment of <name key="Myoporineae">Myoporineae</name> (Myoporinae in M's usage) in B68.03.04, pp. 147-51.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As to the genera of <name key="Myoporineae">Myoporineae</name> they certainly do run much one into another. There appear to me to be four main types</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Myoporum Stamens nearly equal. Ovary of 2, 3, 4 or more perfect cells with one ovule in each</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Pholidia">Pholidia</name>. Stamens didynamous. Ovary of 2 cells with 1 or 2 ovules in each. Endocarp 2- or 4 -celled with 1 seed in each</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Eremophila Stamens didynamous. Ovary of 2 cells with 4 or 6 ovules in each in superposed pairs. Calyx lobes not overlapping at the base. Endocarp separating into 4 one-seeded nuts. Exocarp almost dry</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Stenochilus">Stenochilus</name> Stamens and Ovary of Eremophila. Calyx much imbricate at the base. Endocarp very hard and four-celled. Exocarp succulent</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>But these run into each other especially the two last. <name key="Myoporum%20debile">Myoporum debile</name> has a two-celled ovary with two ovules in each Two or three species of <name key="Stenochilus">Stenochilus</name> have only one pair of ovules in each cell and some species have rather ambiguous fruit. Browns <name key="Eremophila%20alternifolia">Eremophila alternifolia</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>R. Brown (1810), p. 518 discusses <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Eremophila.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> goes better in <name key="Stenochilus">Stenochilus</name> and others are not quite certain I therefore follow you in uniting <name key="Stenochilus">Stenochilus</name> and <name key="Eremodendron">Eremodendron</name> with Eremophila but I think <name key="Pholidia">Pholidia</name> must be retained (including <name key="Pseudopholidia">Pseudopholidia</name> and <name key="Sentis">Sentis</name>) as being as distinct from Eremophila as from Myoporum without any positive limits from either — the latter of course including <name key="Disoon">Disoon</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your <name key="Eremophila%20myoporoides">Eremophila myoporoides</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B65.04.01, p. 23.</p>
               </note> seems to me to be a true Myoporum only differing from M. deserti in the larger flowers. These two species differ from all other Australian Myopora in having constantly regular pentandrous flowers with the base of the corolla lobes perfectly glabrous whilst in all other Australian species I always find only four perfect stamens and only <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">exceedingly rarely</hi>
               </seg> (indeed only once in the very numerous buds I have opened) a fifth imperfect one and always even where described as glabrous I find some hairs at the base of the corolla-lobes.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Browns <name key="Eremophila%20oppositifolia">Eremophila oppositifolia</name> looks very different from E. Cunninghamii although you may be right in considering it as an extreme form. The leaves are almost terete as in E. alternifolia — but I shall compare them again.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Bentham (1863-78), vol . 5, p. 20, treated <seg style="font-style: italic; ">E. cunninghamii</seg> as a synonym of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">E. oppositifolia</seg>.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever yours sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I go abroad next week till September<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>The journey included periods working in various herbaria; see B. Jackson (1906), pp. 213-5.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
